08 Lasso, Ridge, and Elastic-Net Regression in Supervised Learning

Linear regression is a fundamental tool in statistics and machine learning. However, when dealing with high-dimensional data, or when multicollinearity (correlation between predictors) is present, plain linear regression can have limitations. To address these challenges, researchers have introduced penalized regression techniques such as Lasso, Ridge, and Elastic-Net regression. These methods not only help in regularization but also in feature selection.

Regular linear regression minimizes the sum of squares to find the line of best fit, here we out a penalty on the accuracy of the model for the size of the coefficients, large coefficients means larger error and is less accurate compared to regular linear regression to minimize overfitting.

LASSO minimizes l1 norm (absolute value norm) pushing out predictors, assigning coefficient of 0s essentially saying its not there.

Ridge minimizes the l2 norm (degree 2 norm) always keep every single predictor variable even if its super small

Elastic net combines both.

In this lecture note, we will dive deep into these methods, understand their mathematical underpinnings, and apply them using the R language.

Variable Importance

Variable importance provides insights into which features are most influential in predicting the response variable. For Lasso and Ridge regression, the magnitude of regression coefficients can be a proxy for feature importance.

In the context of regularized regression, variables with larger absolute coefficients are more important. Remember, though, Lasso regression can shrink coefficients to zero, indicating that the corresponding feature is not important.

Regularization Techniques and Hyperparameters

Regularization techniques, such as Lasso, Ridge, and Elastic-Net, introduce a penalty to the loss function. This penalty controls the complexity of the model, reducing the chance of overfitting.

Key hyperparameters in these techniques include:

  • \(\lambda\): Regularization strength. A higher value of \(\lambda\) will impose a stronger penalty, potentially shrinking coefficients closer to zero.

  • \(\alpha\): Mix ratio in Elastic-Net regression. Dictates the balance between Lasso and Ridge penalties.

  • alpha of 0(ridge) or 1(LASSO) youll get ridge or lasso and something in between is a combination

Selecting the right hyperparameters is crucial. Techniques like cross-validation can be helpful in finding optimal values.

Ridge Regression

Ridge regression introduces a penalty term for the magnitude of coefficients. This penalty term ensures that the model remains robust even when there is multicollinearity.

Mathematical Formulation

The cost function for ridge regression can be written as: \[ J(\theta) = \sum_{i=1}^{n} (y_i - x_i^T \theta)^2 + \lambda \sum_{j=1}^{p} \theta_j^2 \] Where: - \(y_i\) is the actual value. - \(x_i\) is the feature vector. - \(\theta\) is the coefficient vector. - \(\lambda\) is the regularization parameter.

Squares the coefficients, add them up, multiplying by lambda and add it to the error term of our model. Ridge will never kick out any of our variables. ## R Implementation

glmnet_ridge <- glmnet::glmnet(
  x = M[,v_predictors] %>%                                  # x: predictors
    dplyr::filter(M$train_test == "Train") %>%
    as.matrix(),
  y = M$box_cox_sale_price[M$train_test == "Train"],        # y: target variable
  alpha = 0,
  lambda = 0.5
)
glmnet_ridge

Lasso Regression

Lasso regression, like ridge regression, also adds a penalty term. However, the difference is in the type of penalty. Lasso can shrink some coefficients exactly to zero, making it useful for feature selection.

Mathematical Formulation

The cost function for lasso regression is: \[ J(\theta) = \sum_{i=1}^{n} (y_i - x_i^T \theta)^2 + \lambda \sum_{j=1}^{p} |\theta_j| \]

instead of squaring the coefficients, takes abs value then add it up, multiple by lamba and add it to the error term. This will set a coefficent to 0 doing variable selection for us. ## R Implementation

Again, we’ll use the glmnet package and the mtcars dataset.

glmnet_lasso <- glmnet::glmnet(
  x = M[,v_predictors] %>%
    dplyr::filter(M$train_test == "Train") %>%
    as.matrix(),
  y = M$box_cox_sale_price[M$train_test == "Train"],
  alpha = 1,
  lambda = 0.025
)

Elastic-Net Regression

Elastic-Net regression combines the penalties of ridge and lasso regression. It can be especially useful when there are multiple correlated features.

Mathematical Formulation

The cost function for elastic-net regression is: \[ J(\theta) = \sum_{i=1}^{n} (y_i - x_i^T \theta)^2 + \lambda \left( \alpha \sum_{j=1}^{p} \theta_j^2 + (1-\alpha) \sum_{j=1}^{p} |\theta_j| \right) \] Where \(\alpha\) is a mix ratio between ridge (when \(\alpha = 0\)) and lasso (when \(\alpha = 1\)).

Uses alpha to do a weighted average of the 2 aspects from ridge and lasso (the squaring of the coefficients and the absolute value).

glmnet_elasticnet <- glmnet::glmnet(
  x = M[,v_predictors] %>%
    dplyr::filter(M$train_test == "Train") %>%
    as.matrix(),
  y = M$box_cox_sale_price[M$train_test == "Train"],
  alpha = 0.5,
  lambda = 0.025
)
glmnet_elasticnet

Regularization Techniques, Hyperparameters, and Cross-validation

Regularization in regression models, particularly in Lasso, Ridge, and Elastic-Net, introduces the complexity of determining the optimal hyperparameters, mainly the penalty parameter \(\lambda\). The challenge lies in determining a \(\lambda\) that generalizes well to unseen data.

Cross-validation with cv.glmnet

The cv.glmnet function from the glmnet package in R performs k-fold cross-validation to determine the best \(\lambda\). This function automatically tries out many different \(\lambda\) values and uses cross-validation to determine which one results in the lowest prediction error.

cv.glmnet_ridge <- glmnet::cv.glmnet(
  x = M[,v_predictors] %>%
    dplyr::filter(M$train_test == "Train") %>%
    as.matrix(),
  y = M$box_cox_sale_price[M$train_test == "Train"],
  alpha = 0
)
cv.glmnet_ridge
## 
## Call:  glmnet::cv.glmnet(x = M[, v_predictors] %>% dplyr::filter(M$train_test ==      "Train") %>% as.matrix(), y = M$box_cox_sale_price[M$train_test ==      "Train"], alpha = 0) 
## 
## Measure: Mean-Squared Error 
## 
##     Lambda Index Measure      SE Nonzero
## min  0.122    85  0.0269 0.00237      78
## 1se  0.494    70  0.0290 0.00224      78

This function identifies 2 lambdas for us, the minimum penalty and the largets lambda within 1 standard error of the minimum. so we went with lambda = 0.494 or 0.5 for steakholders

## Call:  glmnet::cv.glmnet(x = M[, v_predictors] %>% dplyr::filter(M$train_test ==      "Train") %>% as.matrix(), y = M$box_cox_sale_price[M$train_test ==      "Train"], alpha = 0.5) 
## 
## Measure: Mean-Squared Error

## min 0.0134    42  0.0247 0.00277      40
## 1se 0.0448    29  0.0269 0.00270      29
plot(
  x = cv.glmnet_elasticnet
)

From the resulting plot, the y-axis shows the mean squared error, and the x-axis shows the log-lambda sequence. The two vertical lines on the plot represent:

  1. The lambda value that gives the minimum mean cross-validated error.
  2. The largest lambda value such that the error is within one standard error of the minimum.

We like larger lambdas because it shrinks down coefficients more. From the plots, we havent lost a lot of accuracy but we are able shrink out more variables protecting us from multicolinearity and overfitting.

Selecting the Optimal \(\lambda\) (How to extract the value)

  • Lambda that Minimizes the Metric: This is the value of \(\lambda\) that gives the smallest prediction error based on cross-validation. It can be extracted with:
cv.glmnet_lasso$lambda.min
## [1] 0.0081
  • Lambda within 1 Standard Error: Sometimes, a more regularized model is desired even if the prediction error is slightly higher. This approach provides a simpler model. The \(\lambda\) value within one standard error of the minimum can be extracted with:
cv.glmnet_lasso$lambda.1se
## [1] 0.022

The decision on which \(\lambda\) to use depends on the goals of the analysis. If predictive accuracy is paramount, then the lambda that minimizes the metric is appropriate. If model interpretability and simplicity are more important, then the lambda within 1 standard error might be more suitable.

Conclusion Summary

  • Ridge regression penalizes the squared magnitude of coefficients, providing a solution to multicollinearity but doesn’t perform feature selection.

  • Lasso regression uses an absolute penalty leading to some coefficients being exactly zero, hence facilitating feature selection.

  • Elastic-Net is a hybrid of ridge and lasso, balancing between them based on a mixing parameter.
